      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(tls): add subjectAltName to auto-generated gateway self-signed certificate (fixes #96910)",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\nFixes #96910.\n\nWhen gateway TLS is enabled with `autoGenerate=true` (the default), the self-signed certificate is generated with only `CN=openclaw-gateway` and no `subjectAltName` extension. Node.js ≥17 ignores the CN for hostname/IP verification per RFC 6125, so the CLI probe to `wss://127.0.0.1:18789` fails with:\n\n```\nGateway probe failed: Hostname/IP does not match certificate's altnames: IP: 127.0.0.1 is not in the cert's list:\n```\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\n`openssl req -x509` was invoked without `-addext subjectAltName=...`, producing a CN-only certificate. Modern TLS stacks require SANs for hostname matching, especially IP addresses.\n\n## User Impact\n\nUsers with `gateway.tls.autoGenerate=true` (default) no longer get TLS handshake failures when the CLI or other local clients connect to the gateway by IP or hostname.\n\n## Changes Made\n\n- `src/infra/tls/gateway.ts`: Added `import os from \"node:os\"` and appended `-addext \"subjectAltName=DNS:localhost,DNS:<hostname>,IP:127.0.0.1,IP:::1\"` to the `openssl req` arguments in `generateSelfSignedCert`.\n- `src/infra/tls/gateway.test.ts`: Added regression test verifying the generated certificate contains the expected SAN entries.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- **Unit tests:** `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs run src/infra/tls/gateway.test.ts` — 8/8 passed\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n**Environment:** Linux, OpenClaw 2026.6.10 (this fix), Node 24.13.1, OpenSSL 3.x\n\n**Step 1: Generate certificate with fix** — `loadGatewayTlsRuntime` with `autoGenerate=true`.\n\n**Step 2: Verify subjectAltName via openssl:**\n\n```\n$ openssl x509 -in gateway-cert.pem -noout -ext subjectAltName\nX509v3 Subject Alternative Name:\n    DNS:localhost, DNS:LIN-66D8BD4EA2C, IP Address:127.0.0.1, IP Address:0:0:0:0:0:0:0:1\n```\n\n**Step 3: Verify subject (unchanged):**\n\n```\n$ openssl x509 -in gateway-cert.pem -noout -subject\nsubject=CN = openclaw-gateway\n```\n\n**Step 4: Strict TLS identity check (Node.js tls.checkServerIdentity):**\n\nA real TLS server was started with the generated cert. A client connected with `rejectUnauthorized: false` to bypass self-signed rejection, then `tls.checkServerIdentity` was called for `127.0.0.1` and `localhost`:\n\n```\nConnected!\ncert subjectaltname: DNS:localhost, DNS:LIN-66D8BD4EA2C, IP Address:127.0.0.1, IP Address:0:0:0:0:0:0:0:1\n✅ STRICT TLS CHECK PASSED for 127.0.0.1\n✅ STRICT TLS CHECK PASSED for localhost\n```\n\n**Before fix** (simulated by verifying a CN-only cert):\n```\n❌ Hostname/IP does not match certificate's altnames: IP: 127.0.0.1 is not in the cert's list\n```\n\n- ✅ Self-signed cert now contains subjectAltName with `DNS:localhost`, `DNS:<hostname>`, `IP:127.0.0.1`, `IP:::1`\n- ✅ `tls.checkServerIdentity` passes for both IP and hostname connections\n- ✅ CLI `gateway status` probes no longer fail on strict-TLS Node.js\n\n**What was not tested:** External non-loopback bind addresses (requires security review to determine acceptable SAN scope; the current fix covers loopback and hostname which covers the common case).\n\n- [x] AI-assisted",
        "branch": "fix/issue-96910-gateway-tls-subjectAltName",
